					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    The complete magician guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:Gokou67@aol.com">Zaysus Kal'Vektis</a> | 
		            2/19/2001 3:31:05 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2"><u><b>Introduction</b></u>
All right fledglings, I'm Zaysus, and I'm about to teach you how to be a mage.  This is coming from a level 45 with way more days played than it took me to level there.  I have become so engrossed in EQ that I've known as much if not more than experience 50+ players since I was level 30 or so.  In other words, I know what I’m doing, and I've come to love the mage class and I will never quit my mage no matter how unwanted I am in groups (this is exaggerated people), or how much they overpower melee classes (this isn’t).

To start off, what you need to do to get through the grueling levels 1-15.  You definitely want to get 16 fast, you start to come into your own then.  Ill try to get you started off, and let you learn the ropes of the class on your own.  This guide only discusses pre-50 elements of the game and the mage class, and I will leave you to discover the rest on your own if you haven’t by the twenties or so =)

<u><b>Spell lines</b></u>
<u> Direct Damage (DD)</u>
For mages, DD spells fall under the conjuration school of magic, which includes all of your summoning spells.  If anybody is interested in why damage is not evocation, its because mage spells are (if EQ was reality) summons, Shock of Blades, Shock of Spikes, Shock of Swords, think of them as summoning blades to strike the opponent.  They do a very good amount of damage for their levels (8, 24, and 44) and have great mana:damage ratios, only rivaled by wizards.  These spells will be your bread and butter for most of your career.  The only strategy involved in using them is taunt factor.  And this you need to practice, practice, practice.  Learn how much damage your pet needs to do, how far back to stand, and how many nukes you can cast before something turns on you.  Less of an issue with earth pets, but if you are good, you can solo with fire/water/air and never be touched.

<u> Bolts (DD) </u>
Bolts are great spells.  They are efficient DD, highly damaging for their level (at 34 even outdamaging a wizard) and overall good to have.  They have downsides however.  As the name suggests, they must be fired AT a mob, they do not automatically hit like most DD.  They are fired like a projectile, and even minute terrain objects can get in the way, negating all the damage.  If you learn how to use bolts correctly and in the right situations (i.e.  not usually in dungeon areas with multiple melee'ers) and you learn the tricks of them (firing backwards, off higher platforms, etc.) they are amazing.  Always make sure to keep a good line of sight unless you are using the back-firing trick, which I will not discuss here.

<u> Area Effect (AE) and Point Blank (PBAE) </u>
These spells are definitely limited in their usefulness, but if used in the right situations, can do a ton of damage for comparatively less mana than DD.  The trick to using area effect spells is that they are ONLY mana efficient when there are 2 or more targets under the effect of the spell.  For instance, if you cast the level 12 column of fire (coincidentally the only non PB area spell mages receive) on a single creature, you are doing a maximum of 51 damage for 65 mana.  An insanely terrible ratio.  Where your level 8 spell (blades) is still doing 35 for 30 mana.  However, when you up the number of targets to two or three, you can see how these spells become useful.  Casting the level 8 DD on three creatures does a maximum of 105 damage total, for 90 mana, but using column of fire, you can do 153 damage for only 65 mana.  The only time I have used area effect spells efficiently pre-scintillation (you'll learn about scintillation later) is in a group doing AE kiting.  You get a wiz, druid, and mage together, or any combination of those, wizard area effect snares more than one mob (mob=creature), and everyone blasts away with AEs.  Its a bit tough when you have to get into the thick and cast, but usually you will not be attacked due to the fact that they are chasing the highly damaging wizard.

<u> Damage Shields (DS, FS) </u>
Mages, no matter what anyone else tells you, have the most damaging "damage shields" in the game.  You will see other lines of spells called damage shields.  The enchanter's rune for instance, or wizard/necro's skin spell line, absorbs damage to an extent before wearing off, but the more common damage shields of a mage or druid (mages are also called fire shields), you cast on your party members, and every time they are hit by melee, damage is done to the attacker.  This is extremely effective damage because **it cannot be resisted by any means** as long as melee is being done, and it is incredibly mana efficient.  The most important thing to remember about these spells is that they do not count towards your damage, your tanks, or your pets, so they add no taunt factor, unless you cast it on a tank during battle, in which case the mob considers it assisting the enemy.  Your lowest level shield does 5-6 damage each time your pet, you, or whomever else you cast it on is hit.  It eventually ups to 25 and then 33 post-50.  When you solo without the fire pet. ALWAYS have the damage shield up on your pet (you'll learn more about the fire pets shield later on).  The added bonus of these shields is the fact that they add fire resist, which can be helpful in certain areas.

<u> Shielding</u>
There is not much to say about the shielding line except that, if you are low level and still tanking for your pet a bit, keep it up.  If you are higher level and will be getting hit, keep it up, or if you need extra magic resist, keep it up.  They add a good amount to AC, HP, and magic resist (MR).  The line begins with minor shielding at level 1 and ends with shield of the magi.

<u> Phantom Armor</u>
These spells can be explained in a few sentences.  They are buffs which add to your AC, but a while ago, a great component was added to them, they now give you HP regen, for all you taking mages out there =).  They start off with phantom leather costing 1 cat's eye agate, and go up progressively from there, ending with 4.  Useful spell in some situations, don’t waste your money on cats eye if you are short.

<u> Damage Over Time (DoT) </u>
Many classes get DoT spells, they are spells that you cast on an opponent, and instead of doing all their damage at once, they do it over a period of 30 seconds or a minute, or whatever.  Every 6 seconds is called a 'tick', and this is when the damage is done.  Mages were given 2 DoT's with velious, called elemental maelstrom and wrath of elements.  They are not as mana efficient as other class DoT's but they do good damage in a small amount of time, and have less taunt factor than DD spells.

<u> Burnout</u>
Burnout I, II, III, and IV, are pet buffs. They add progressively more AC, STR, and attack speed (yay!) to your pet.  Always keep these on, unless of course...you like your pet being less effective.

<u> Malise</u>
Malise is a great spell which we get several upgrades to.  There’s not much to say about it except, you should usually be pulling your fights with it all the time, except in the rare cases where you think you know they will not resist your spells.  But even then, it's very useful to use this spell, because it will help your earth pet's root or your air pet's stun to stick, or your other pets spells (worthless as they are).  Overall, one of the best spell lines we get.

<u> Misc. Spells</u>
Invisibility - I believe this one is self explanatory.
Reclaim Energy - Destroys your pet and gives you some mana back for it.
Flare - The most worthless spell in the entire game.
Eye of Zomm - Summons an eye which you can take control of and run around as for a portion of a minute.
Monster Summoning - Summons a pet with a random property from one of your pets (including the decoy template).  The cool thing is that it makes your pet look like some creature from the zone (running down the oasis shoreline with an SG pet is always fun =\~ ).  Only real use for this is to have the old version of the fire pet after level 50 when our coolest pet is ruined, ruined, ruined, ruined, ruined. =(   I’m not too happy about the fire pet change if you didn't notice.

<u> Summons</u>
Ahhh, summons.  Why else would you be a summoner.  Well, its not for these spells I can assure you.  There is a very limited use for your summon spells, with the notable exception of some.  Your weapon spells generally suck, except at level 8 if you need a magic weapon for your pet (they don’t hit magical until level 12), and at 24-39 when you should give your pet two level 1 daggers just so he dual wields.  Heatstone (level 16) and Coldstone (level 29) go in your neck or ammo slot and give you infravision and ultravision respectively.  They are always useful to have around if you’re a human or erudite, or a gnome or high elf that wants better vision.  Dark elves buy the spell anyway, people will ask you for them.  Sword of Runes, used to be a great spell, give them to your pets and they would proc constantly almost, a 35ish damage spell that worked on everybody despite being summoned only when players used it.  Well Verant nerfed these like everything else, and dropped pet proc rates to the same crappy ones as players.  They are now useless.  Summon Food/Cornucopia, and Summon Drink/Everfount.  Always useful, you’ll have infinite food and drink.  The level 1 versions are limited as they only summon 1 at a time, but the level 24 spells summon up 20 at once. Black bread and nasty water. Yum.  The bags you can summon (dimensional pocket, hole) give you a bag that reduces weight, but when you log off everything inside goes poof, or when you go linkdead.  Don’t put important loot inside, I would suggest  carrying normal bags.  Use with care.  Summon arrows/throwing daggers.  Pullers will sometimes ask you for arrows, daggers are useful if your tank needs to pull something from a distance and has no bow.  They don’t need skill, as long as they throw it and miss, the mob will come running.  Again, limited usefulness.  Summon Ring of Flight, level 39, put the ring on, right click, and up you go.  It has two charges of levitate which makes you float, useful in many situations, and lasts longer than normal levitate, also it does not require bat wings to cast as levitate does.  You'll probably want this spell.  Modulating Rod.  When I got it I thought, wow, a rod that you right click and it turns your HP into mana.  Well I was rudely awakened when I realized it takes out 225 HP and give you back only 150 mana, the worst part being that it costs 200 mana to make.  Buy it, have fun with it, give it to and kill some newbies (j/k), they’re actually a lot less useful than people make them out to be.  Give them to people in your group in case of a mana emergency.  Once again, limited usefulness.  But now we come to....

<u> Pets (Elementals, Summonings, Conjurations, Vocerations) </u>
Pets.  THIS is why you are a mage, not because of the terribly abundant and underpowered summons, because of the terribly abundant and overpowered pets (that statement becomes obsolete after 50, because Verant screwed our pets up, just wait until you hear about the fire pet).  They are your bread and butter.  They keep you alive.  You have no method of escape other than keeping your pet alive to run, or running while that earth pets root sticks.  Following is a description of each type of pet and the situations to use them in.  Add to this with your own experience, I'm just guiding you, not telling you what to do.

<I>Earth:<I> The solo pet.  (solo pet my ass)  Everybody says, use earth for solo, but if you're a good magician, you don’t need to.  You use more efficient methods.  Earth is great for soloing after 50, or right before a new spell level, when you need the extra HP to take harder mobs down.  The earth pet has the highest HP of any pet, casts root on your enemies (don’t get too excited, its alot shorter and weaker than normal root) and has incredibly low AC.  It gets hit I would say 80% of the time by blue con mobs.  Its basically a durable punching bag.  Sit and nuke away with this thing.  There is a severe problem with earth pets rooting however.  If something is running away from you, your pet beating on it, and it becomes rooted, it will turn around and fight until the root wears off, effectively doing unneeded damage to your pet, sometimes getting him killed if the fight was tough.  Be careful with this.

<I>Water:<I> This is the all around pet.  It can be used in any and all situations.  If you are good at your nuke/taunt control, Id suggest using him instead of the earth blob for soloing.  There is a good reason for this.  Water has almost as much HP as earth, regens HP much faster, is immune to poison and disease (matters sometimes) and get hit less often due to higher AC.  Also, it does not root, it casts a damage spell, which causes it to drop things faster (but not much) in the long run.  Overall a good pet, especially when you need a tank but don’t want the earth pet's root.

<I>Air:</I> Air is a situational pet, some will tell you.  It can be soloed with, but it is usually inefficient to do so.  It casts probably the most useful spell of all the pets.  Stun.  This makes it the ideal pet for fighting casting mobs because it has the opportunity to interrupt casting.  This is also the ideal pet for grouping because it stuns creatures, preventing damage to your tanks.  It also, although some will disagree, has a decent amount of HP.  It is not too far below the water pet, only the fire pet has marginally lower HP than the rest.  Air also has the highest AC.  This is somewhat noticeable, but not by much.  Overall, a well-made pet, he can actually stand up to some punishment, and is usually good in groups.

<I>Fire:</I> I love my little glowing ember blob!  Fire is my favorite pet for one reason, if you get good at soloing with it, you are going to do massive amounts of damage, and its NOT hard to outdamage the pet to get the exp, even though you may be thinking otherwise.  This is because the damage shield that it casts on itself does the pets level+2 damage, which is way, way more than your damage shield that you can cast at the same level.  While they do not have alot of HP, and may need a couple heals during a fight, you only need to nuke once or twice in most situations (unless you are fighting tougher mobs, or are using this pet right before a new spell level).  The reason you can outdamage it so easily is that its damage shield's damage is not accounted for when it calculates the pets damage, nor is it accounted for when yours is calculated.  Therefore, if the pet does, theoretically, 400 damage melee, and the shield does 400 damage, you only have to do 401 damage to get the exp, not 801.  Using a fire pet (can we say yetis 34-40) will definitely get your nuke/taunt skills up to par.  I went through hell level 35, all the way to one bubble into level 40, in 2 days in the yeti caves.  Fire pet baby. =)  This little guy is tough.  Guess what happened though, Verant, in their infinite wisdom (praise "The Vision (TM)") decided to completely **** up our fire pets when they gave them to us in kunark.  They now cast wizard spells. YIPEE! My level 44 pet does more damage over the course of a fight.  Its fun watching him get resisted, melee for 27 (can we say level 29 pets here?), gate himself, cast a 2 damage shield instead of his great old one..and then on top of that, dispell the debuffs that the group put on the mob! WOOHOO!  Thumbs down: Verant.

Mages also get three other "types" of pets.  Although they are not really types, but rather single pets with different functions.   Dyzil's Deafening Decoy, basically is made to do low dmg but have high taunt/defense.  Rage of Zomm is the exact opposite, all offense, and then there is the epic pet, which I will have a special section on at the end.


<u><b>Hunting Guide</b></u>
The hunting areas here are just suggestions for leveling fast, I did a ton of RP, questing, building factions, player relations, among other things throughout my career.  This guide, although based on the combat aspect of the game, does not in any way suggest that you should power level to 50, because you will probably not enjoy yourself much, and cause unwanted stress and frustration.

<u><b>Level 1-3: Generic Newbie</b></u>
You are not much different than any other character except for a few notable exceptions.  you can summon a dagger which is a bit better than your newbie dagger, and you can summon your own food and drink, so all you need is money for the spells (not a problem if you are twinking, which I would advocate, but not to the extent to which you don’t need to use your spells to solo).  A little money and some items never hurt, but believe me people, it is WAY more fun to get your own items throughout the course of the game, I quit all four of my twinks 15-30 because its just not fun to be overpowered for your level and not have the opportunity to do it all on your own.  Of course, people will disagree with me, and that’s entirely up to personal opinion, I’m just giving you my take.

<u><b>Level 4-7: Your Newbie Mage</b></u>
You finally have your pets, or hopefully one of them at least, if you’re short on cash.  I would suggest the water and air pets at this level.  Fire has far too little HP to be worth the extra damage, and earth gets hit too much.  Especially when you get level 6 or so and start fighting poisoning creatures, water pets can help alot in this department due to their innate resistance to poison (see pet section).  I would suggest fighting in your local semi-newbie area here (orcs in kelethin, kobolds in steamfont, qeynos hills, east commons/nro, as examples).  Easy levels, really.

<u><b>Level 8-11: You can kill things! </b></u>
Finally, you get a damage spell that does a good deal of damage.  For around the same amount of mana, you can do 30 damage with magic base.  Also, you get your first bolt which is just a tad more efficient, but you’re going to have to practice at this level, because its the first one you have, and you wont be used to wasting your mana when it runs into things.  You also get your first damage shield, which you should always keep up on your pet unless you are using fire (which I don’t recommend at this level).  The pets are great at this level for this point in the game.  Go kill things in your local dungeon, or secondary newbie area (ecommons, nro, crushbone, blackburrow, wherever).  Always give your pet a summoned staff, so they will do more damage than they would without it (this only works here and with weak level 12 pets).

<u><b>Level 12-15: You can't kill things! </b></u>
Level 12 is a crappy spell level, really.  Unless you start your mage after the rain spell changes go in, and they will do good damage, you don’t get any DD at this level, and your pets get a very minor upgrade.  What I mean is, at level 8 you can summon a yellow pet, you can at 16 too, but for some strange reason, level 12's max pet cons even.  On the plus side, you get your first Burnout spell, which increases pet stats and effectiveness (see spells section above).  Go to lavastorm, mutilate things with ward summoned (imps, elementals, drakes (with magic)).  Steamfont works wonders too.

<u><b>Level 16-19: The fun begins</b></u>
Now level 16, IMO, is alot of fun.  You get a DD spell that does 96 damage, which, if you are new to the game, will seem like all the power in the world to you =).  Your pets also get a major upgrade from the crap that is level 12, and you can summon heatstones (for all you human/erudite mages) that go in your ammo or neck slot and grant you infravision.  You should probably fight in east karana, oasis, or if you are good take aviak guards in lake rathe at this level.  If you have kunark, which I will assume you do, go to the overthere zone, I’m going to leave the process up to you to discover, just don’t take the boat and merrily stroll on into the town.  And find the warslik's woods entrance, solo there, the experience is awesome.  At this level, you will also need to start researching certain spells (you can buy your pet spells for 16 and 20 in the ocean of tears if you are too lazy to research).

<u><b>Level 20-23: Give me more power! More! </b></u>
More fun again, your pets are much cooler due to the increase in physical size (they’ll get bigger still!), and your bolt, if you are proficient in using them, now does over 100 damage.  Buy elemental shield, it will be useful when fighting casting or element based mobs.  you get a good upgrade to your damage shield, and you are, in general, way more effective.  At this level, lake rathe, south karana, lake of ill omen, probably more places in kunark, are effective leveling areas.  Its not too hard to get to 24 here (Id say lake rathe is the best and easiest if you know what you’re doing and its not too busy when you play, treants will work wonders if you can get into the group in south karana.).  24 is awesome, get there fast!  You should be working on your focus items by now and have at least one or two by level 30, hunting in cazic thule is great experience and can help this along alot.

<u><b>Level 24-28: Hahaha, look at me kill things! </b></u>
If you like the little things about the game, if appearance means alot to you, you'll love what you get at 24.  Your spells look different now when you cast them.  There are more particles, and you'll in general feel much cooler.  You get two spells at this level which you will be using for a looong time, so get used to them.  Malise, which you will use until level 43 for certain, and shock of blades, which you will most likely be using until 43 as a weak secondary nuke (however after 40 I just dropped it for blaze/cinder bolt).  Malise is your new pull spell, and you will get many less resists with it.  Get to 26 or 27 wherever you can, lake of ill omen in kunark is great.  Also, when you get to 26 or 27 you may want to head to ocean of tears, and, if you don’t care about your faction, mutilate the dwarves and sisters one by one until you get to level 29, which I think you'll like, because you get to use your spiffy new fire pet to solo =).

<u><b>Level 29-33: Become one with the fiery blob</b></u>
I loved level 29 because you could finally solo things with the fire pet, viably.  Although they nerfed the rune swords which increased pet damage tremendously (I wont get into detail here), your fire pet at 29, is still a monster compared to what you’ve had before it.  It can pretty much solo a mid twenties mob with no help from you save buffing it with burnout 2, another great spell which you get at this level.  If you want to know the absolute fastest way through, I would say just kill the dwarves and sisters in OOT till your head falls off, and you’ll be 34 very quickly, if you are patient.  However, I wouldn’t recommend this as I said before, I'd rather promote grouping, adventuring, etc.  Focus items work on 29, even before.  Don’t listen to the people that say otherwise, its just not as noticeable the lower level you get. You also get a new damage shield upgrade at this level which does good damage, but who cares, you’re going to use your fire pet.  You are going to use your fire pet....aren’t you?  Learn your fire pet tactics.  Learn your fire pet tactics.  Learn your fire pet tactics.  Learn your fire pet tactics.  Learn your fire pet tactics.  Learn your fire pet tactics.  Learn your fire pet tactics.  Understood?

<u><b>Level 34-38: Mage looks like a wizard</b></u>
You know the Aerosmith song "Dude Looks Like a Lady"? That’s where I got the title from.  But I’m bored, so feel free to laugh your ass off at my periodic spurts of idiocy, please.  The reason I titled it that is because at this level, your nukes are awesome.  Your bolt does more damage in a single spell (nevermind the mana/dmg ration or cast time fools!) =) than a wizard does at 34.  And blaze is awesome too.  There is one problem with these spells however, and that is you will be using them for 9 levels. Blah.  They’re good enough though, so no complaints from the likes of you.  Your pets also get a major overhaul.  They now hit harder, can tank a good amount, and, if you have your focus items like a good little mage, get bigger in size.  Hold the focus item in your hand to cast the spell, and your pet will come out as a nice sized beastie.  Get used to the size, you’re going to be using pets like it for 15 levels.  Go wherever you want.  Have fun, please, you’re fairly powerful.  Have fun trying to take down a griffin, its an extremely difficult challenge at this level (unless you have jboots).  Get in a giant group, something.  Or you could do the mage thing and level, level, level.  Lower guk, old world dungeons, whatever.  Best places for experience are hands down: Yeti caves in dreadlands being number one if you are good with a fire pet, and the overthere being number 2.  Have fun, like I said, you're powerful now.

<u><b>Level 39-43: Go kill a giant</b></u>
Go, now, go get revenge, kill em cause you want to, kill em cause you have to, kill em cause I said so, just do one giant before you get to 44.  From now on your pet is treated like an NPC, and regens massive amounts of HP per tick, while your lowest summon will hit for 34, and your highest 34 summon does the same, the 39 pets tank a great deal better, especially earth.  And then of course you have the fact that they regen about 10 times faster than the last level pets, and bam, right off the bat you have the making of a great level.  Add to that a new fire shield which does ~20 damage, and the ability to summon those oh-so-fun rings of levitation, weeeeeee.  Your worst hell level ever is coming up.  Want to level fast? Dreadlands dreadlands dreadlands.

<u><b>Level 44-48: It just keeps getting better! </b></u>
Now you can kill newbies by summoning up modulation rods and giving them out to newbies who have less than 225 HP =).  The rods, which take away 225 HP when you right click them and give you 150 mana in return, are good, but not great.  Oh well, they have their uses, and can sometimes save entire raids, but they are certainly limited in their use.  I wont go into mod rod strategies here. DONT REALLY KILL THE POOR HELPLESS NEWBIES!  Well, only if you want to.  Oh by the way, your pets got way better, your DD does 580 damage (yipee, no more fire!), and your DoT (yes we get those too) does 600 damage.  Oh ya, put away malise in the back of your spellbook, its upgrade time in the form of malisement.  And you’ll notice a huge difference (sorry you cant feel my sarcasm right now...) but really folks, it is noticeably better.  If you want money at this level, you can go get a partner or two and camp some stuff, or go kill Gornit on seafury island in OOT, and get mad cash, and your experience actually moves with every kill even in 45.  Bloodgill goblins in LOIO, (glacier yetis if you are really good), dreadlands is still awesome experience, and very, very, very rarely (but it happens) you just MIGHT by some strange twist of time and space, be able to get into a karnor's group before you’re 49.

<u><b>Level 49-50: /sit on, /cheer Jabober</b></u>
Guess what, your pet grew up again, but this time he decided to take steroids.  Uh-oh, you know what that means?  That means that your earth pet's HP went up, instead of the usual percentage of maybe 15%-35% or so, by upwards of 150%, almost 200%.  Holy Mary mother of Jesus!  If you were in the old world, you’d be godlike!  But alas, this is the kunark era (smart-assed, sarcastic tone of voice used here), and you’re going to be just as good/bad as everyone else, or so they say.  Who cares anyways, I still consider the spells god-like ...*mumbles about kunark and velious*. (will stop rambling now).  25 point damage shield, 800 point bolt, pets that quad for 56 constantly and can solo a giant like its a large bat (this is the highlight really), burnout III, as if your pets weren’t powerful enough.

<u><b>Conclusion</b></u>
If you need me to tell you anything about 50+, go play a different game, because you didn’t learn much in the amount of time it takes to build a character.  In fact you should have stopped reading this guide at about level 34 or 39, I became sort of nonchalance after that point, more joking, if you hadn't noticed.  In the next installment, I will have a breakdown of mage research, their spells post 50, their roles on big raids (Call of the Hero anyone?), and the epic quest and reward.  Hope this guide enlightened/entertained you just a bit.  Give me some feedback, even if it is "U $ux0r, 1 w@n+ ph@+ L3w+$".  Cant read that?  Sorry, I haven’t practiced my elite much lately.

Have a nice day.
Zaysus Kal'Vektis - 45th agnostic erudite magician of Morell-Thule, proud member of <Heroic Few>.
Gokou67@aol.com


			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
